One-Predictor Linear Model Example

STAT 341, Spring 2023

2023-02-15

Dataset and Plan

I will use the dataset on bridge condition.

bridges <- read.csv("https://sldr.netlify.app/data/bridges.csv") |> 
  # remove closed bridges (Condition.Rating = 0)
  filter(Condition.Rating >= 1) |> 
  # remove bridges supposedly built after data collection
  filter(Year.Built <= 2015)

Predictor & Response

I will model Condition.Rating as a function of Year.Built, thinking that newer bridges may be in better condition (and condition may deteriorate as the bridge ages).

Causal Diagram

I think that older age will result in deteriorated bridge condition. Condition will vary by location and owner (and bridge age may be different depending on location and owner too). It seems there are bridges of different types and sizes; different kinds of bridges may be built more at certain times than others, and bridge type may vary by location too. Bridge type may affect condition and also interact with age (with the amount of deterioration with age being different for different bridge types). Note, the graph below can’t depict the interaction - but note it makes Type a modifier of the age - condition relationship.

So: modeling condition as a function of just age is clearly an oversimplification, and leaves out key confounders and a moderator! (Wish we already knew how to include more variables in our model…)

Model Description

\[\text{Condition}_i \sim \text{Normal}(\mu_i, \sigma)\] \[\mu_i \sim \beta_0 + \beta_1 * \text{Year.Built}\] \[\beta_0 \sim \text{Normal}(-186.5,50)\] \[\beta_1 \sim \text{Normal}(0.1, 1)\] \[\sigma \sim \text{Normal}(1.5, 2)\]

Rationale:

  • Condition ratings go from 1 to 7. I expect them to go down year to year but to take well over a year (maybe 10 years or so?) to deteriorate a level on the scale.
  • The intercept is the expected condition rating of a bridge built in year 0. I guess the oldest bridges in the data might have been built between the 1800s and 1950, and might have a condition rating that is low like 1-2. So if \(\beta_1\) is about 0.1, and I want condition for an 1800 bridge to be about 1. Condition = 1 = \(\beta_0 + \beta_1 *\) 1800, and that would make \(\beta_0\) = 1 - 0.1 * 1800 = -179. Or if the oldest bridge was in 1950, I would be \(\beta_0 = -194\). So I’ll center the prior for the intercept at 186.5 and give it a standard deviation of about 50 because I really could be off by an order of magnitude if my slope guess is wrong.
  • There might be a lot of variation in condition ratings that doesn’t have to do with age alone. So I’ll make \(\sigma\) centered at 1.5 (on a scale of 1-7) with a standard deviation of 2, so observed datapoints might be up to 4 or 6 condition units away from the expected value.

Data Graph

gf_point(Condition.Rating ~ Year.Built, data  = bridges)

Prior Predictive Check

I want to generate a set of simulated Condition.Rating values that are consistent with my prior. Here is one such dataset the same size as the real data:

# draw a simulated slope and intercept from priors
b0 <- rnorm(1, -186.5, 20)
b1 <- rnorm(1, 0.1, 1)
sigma <- rnorm(1, 1.5, 2)
prior_sim <- tibble(
  # use the Year data from the actual dataset
  Year.Built = bridges$Year.Built,
  Sim.Condition = rnorm(nrow(bridges),
                        mean = b0 + b1 * Year.Built,
                        sd = sigma)
)
gf_point(Sim.Condition ~ Year.Built, data = prior_sim)

If we run this a bunch of times to get a sense of the different possibilities implied by my priors, the massive amount of uncertainty implied in these priors becomes clear – the slope could be positive or negative, and the bridge condition ratings in these simulations don’t even come CLOSE to staying within the realistic limits (between 2 and 7).

This suggests that we might want to use other distributions in a way that would enforce the real limits on the support of the condition ratings (they are all between 1-7). We also might want to use less diffuse (more informative) priors, if we can manage to define them.

But for now let’s just try – Can the data overpower this very diffuse prior and find the answer for us when we fit the model?

Fit the Model

bridge_mod <- quap(
  flist = alist(
    Condition.Rating ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu ~ b0 + b1 * Year.Built,
    b0 ~ dnorm(-186.5, 50),
    b1 ~ dnorm(0.1, 1),
    sigma ~ dnorm(1.5, 2)
  ),
  data = bridges)

Sample from Posterior

# note small posterior sample to make posterior predictive sample calcs manageable later
# for smaller datasets (bridges is 17k observations) you may be able to do 1000+
psamp <- extract.samples(bridge_mod, n = 100)

Graph Posterior(s)

gf_dens(~b0, data = psamp, title = 'Intercept\n(Condition.Rating of a bridge built in Year 0)')
## Warning: `stat(density)` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `after_stat(density)` instead.

gf_dens(~b1, data = psamp, title = 'Slope\n(Increase in Condition.Rating for 1-year Increase in Year.Built)')

gf_dens(~sigma, data = psamp, title = 'Sigma\n(Standard deviation of Condition.Rating for one specific Year.Built)')

How to Display the Posterior?

What’s this model doing? It’s fitting a line to the scatter plot of the data.

Lines

We might consider drawing the lines corresponding to our posterior sample to visualize what the model says about the relationship of age and condition.

gf_point(Condition.Rating ~ Year.Built, 
         data = bridges,
         alpha = 0.1) |>
  gf_abline( # draws "line"s given "a" (slope) and "b" (intercept)
    slope = ~b1, # draws one line for each row of psamp
    intercept = ~b0,
    data = psamp,
    alpha = 0.05, # closer to 0 = more transparent
    linewidth = 0.1 # smaller = thinner
  )

Posterior Predictive Distribution

A posterior predictive distribution would be made up of many fake datasets, each one including nrow(bridges) simulated Condition.Rating values. And to simulate new datapoints, we’d take into account the posterior for \(\sigma\) as well as those of the slope and intercept.

psamp <- psamp |>
  # add row numbers to identify each draw from the posterior
  mutate(sim_id = c(1:nrow(psamp))) |>
  rowwise()  |> # one simulation per draw from posteriors
  mutate(
    # mean_condition is the expected response
    # it's a list with one value per row of original data, `bridges`
    mean_condition = list(b0 + b1 * bridges$Year.Built),
    # store predictor data too to make graphs easier later
    year_built = list(bridges$Year.Built)) |>
  mutate(
    # use sigma to simulate how far datapoints are from expected response 
    sim_condition = list(mean_condition +
                           rnorm(n = nrow(bridges), mean = 0, sd = sigma))
    ) |>
  unnest(cols = c(year_built, mean_condition, sim_condition)) |>
  ungroup()

We now have 100 simulated datasets generated based on our fitted model. The simulated datasets look how we’d expect real data to look, if the model were true.

How can we visualize many datasets at once? We can look at just the first 10 datasets to get an idea of what we have done:

gf_point(sim_condition ~ year_built | sim_id,
         data  = psamp |> filter(sim_id <= 10),
         alpha = 0.1) |>
  # dashed lines show ranges observed in real data
  # (not needed if there are not lower/upper bounds on possible values of response)
  gf_hline(yintercept = 7, linetype = 'dashed') |>
  gf_hline(yintercept = 2, linetype = 'dashed')

How does this compare to the actual data?

gf_point(Condition.Rating ~ Year.Built, data = bridges)

The simulated data are more patternless (aside from the linear trend), and go above the top condition rating of 7. The real data has many more very old bridges in good condition (simulated data has none) but otherwise does not look terribly different from the real data.

How else could we show “all” the posterior predictive distribution?

One idea is to make a scatter plot where color intensity corresponds to the number of datapoints in each location. We could then overlay the actual data on top.

Note: this takes a loooong time when the dataset is as large as this one.

gf_density2d_filled(sim_condition ~ year_built, 
                    data  = psamp) |>
  gf_theme(scale_fill_grey('')) |> # use greyscale color palette
  gf_refine(guides(fill = FALSE)) |> # don't show color legend
  # (optional) add the real data
  gf_point(Condition.Rating ~ Year.Built, data =  bridges,
           size = 0.5, alpha = 0.05) # VERY nearly transparent
## Warning: The `<scale>` argument of `guides()` cannot be `FALSE`. Use "none" instead as
## of ggplot2 3.3.4.

Intervals

The methods above are preferred – this one is provided for compatibility with frequentist confidence intervals. It may be more familiar but isn’t “better.”

We can also compute pointwise percentile-based credible intervals for the response. Say we want a confidence level of 95%, so we want to find the 2.5 and 97.5 percentiles of the model-simulated values. To do this, for each unique value of the PREDICTOR of interest, we find the 0.025 and 0.975 quantiles. Then we can plot the credible intervals for the expected response (the line) or simulated new datapoints as a shaded region.

psamp_CIs <- psamp |>
  group_by(year_built) |> # group by unique values of PREDICTOR
  summarise(CrI_line_low = quantile(mean_condition, 0.025),
            CrI_line_high = quantile(mean_condition, 0.975),
            CrI_points_low = quantile(sim_condition, 0.025),
            CrI_points_high = quantile(sim_condition, 0.975))

gf_point(Condition.Rating ~ Year.Built, data = bridges) |>
  gf_ribbon(CrI_line_low + CrI_line_high ~ year_built, 
            data  = psamp_CIs, fill = 'grey24',
            inherit = FALSE) |>
  gf_ribbon(CrI_points_low + CrI_points_high ~ year_built, 
            data  = psamp_CIs, fill = 'grey54',
            inherit = FALSE)

Note: I believe the boundaries of the credible interval for the point cloud would be much narrower if the number of samples from the posterior were much larger – remember, we used only 100 for “speed”!
